t Bacon envisioned brought to fruition. Despite these challenges, Bacon oversaw the planning and implementation of dozens of redesigned urban spaces: the restored colonial neighborhood of Society Hill, the new office development of Penn Center, and the transit-oriented shopping center of Market East.Ed Bacon is the first biography of this charismatic but controversial figure. Gregory L. Heller traces the trajectory of Bacon's two-decade tenure as city planning director, which coincided with a transformational period in American planning history. Edmund Bacon is remembered as a larger-than-life personality, but in Heller's detailed account, his successes owed as much to his savvy negotiation of city politics and the pragmatic particulars of his vision. In the present day, as American cities continue to struggle with shrinkage and economic restructuring, Heller's insightful biography reveals an inspiring portrait of determination and a career-long effort to transform planning ideas into reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBacon, Edmund N. 0aCity planners -- Pennsylvania -- Philadelphia -- Biography. 0aCity planning -- Pennsylvania -- Philadelphia -- History -- 20th century. 0aPhiladelphia (Pa.) -- History -- 20th century. 4aArchitecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aAutobiography.  aBiography.  aBooks of Regional Interest.  aPublic Policy.  aUrban Studies.1 aGarvin, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarvin, Alexander.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Back